  "summary": "Happy Ghasts path find into fire",
  "environment_raw": null,
  "description": "Happy ghasts can path find into fire. This was observed with soul fire. Unknown if applies to regular fire. n n",
  "Steps to Reproduce": "1. Create a new Creative world in the Nether.\n2. Locate a Soul Sand Valley biome.\n3. Ensure that the game mode is set to Creative to avoid taking damage from fire.\n4. Place a block of Soul Sand on the ground.\n5. Surround the Soul Sand with at least two blocks of Soul Fire, ensuring the fire is lit.\n6. Use the command '/summon happy_ghast ~ ~ ~' to spawn a Happy Ghast nearby.\n7. Observe the Happy Ghast's movement and pathfinding behavior as it approaches the Soul Fire.\n8. Confirm whether the Happy Ghast enters the Soul Fire without taking damage. \n9. Repeat the steps with regular fire by replacing the Soul Fire with a block of regular Fire to check for similar behavior.",
  "Environment": "Minecraft Java Edition Version 1.21.8",
  "Observed Behavior": "Happy Ghasts exhibit unintended pathfinding behavior that allows them to navigate into fire blocks, specifically observed with soul fire. When a Happy Ghast comes within proximity of soul fire, it will move towards and enter the fire block, potentially resulting in the mob being set on fire. This behavior raises concerns about the AI's handling of fire hazards, as it is expected that mobs would avoid fire sources due to the damaging effects. \n\nCurrently, it is unclear whether this pathfinding behavior extends to regular fire or if it is exclusive to soul fire. Further investigation is required to determine if Happy Ghasts can also pathfind into standard fire blocks or if their AI treats these two fire types differently. \n\nThis issue may affect gameplay by allowing Happy Ghasts to unintentionally take damage from fire, which could influence player interactions and strategies when dealing with these mobs in the Nether environment.",
  "Expected Behavior": "Happy Ghasts should not be able to pathfind into fire, including soul fire. Instead, they should exhibit behavior that avoids fire blocks, as they are flying entities. Ideally, when a Happy Ghast approaches a fire source, it should redirect its path to maintain a safe distance, preventing it from entering or colliding with the fire. This behavior aligns with the general mechanics of flying mobs in Minecraft, which typically avoid hazards that can cause damage or impede their movement.",
